               <desc type="site-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000004-2">
                     The Baoguo Monastery in Zhejiang, Ningbo is a historic Buddhist monastery protected by the National Cultural Heritage Administration. The original date of the site’s founding is unknown, but the complex was later destroyed in the year 845, rebuilt in 880, and renamed Baoguo Monastery. Baoguo Monastery is nestled in Ling Mountain (Lingshan 靈山) between the Xiangbi Peak (Xiangbifeng 象鼻峰) and Shiyan Peak (Shiyanfeng 獅岩峰), and only the south side is exposed to downhill. The monastery itself is also surrounded by water: Ci River (Cijiang 慈江) runs at the foot of the mountain and eight streams cross through the mountain. The building complex is roughly oriented north-south, and is more precisely sitting northwest and facing southeast (Xu, Qiu 72). It is symmetrical along the central axis with the exception of a few smaller buildings attached to the west and east sides of the complex. Throughout the <term subtype="dynasty" ref="keyword/k000074">Song Dynasty</term>, new buildings were constructed while maintaining symmetry around the existing central axis. By the <term subtype="dynasty" ref="keyword/k000076">Southern Song Dynasty</term> (南宋, 1127-1279), the complex’s layout was similar to the style of the Five Mountains and Ten Monasteries“五山十剎” defined by the Imperial Court (Guo). The most drastic reconstructions were done during the time of <term subtype="dynasty" ref="keyword/k000051">Ming</term>-<term subtype="dynasty" ref="keyword/k000070">Qing</term> (明清) and the layout is similar to common Ming-Qing Buddhist monasteries. The central axis of the complex is now preserved  in the three steps progression, moving from bottom to top, the Celestial Kings Hall (Tianwangdian 天王殿), <placeName ref="/place/000132">Mahāvīra Treasure Hall (Daxiongbaodian 大雄寶殿)</placeName>, then the Dharma Hall (fatang 法堂) and sutra repository tower (cangjinglou 藏經樓) along the central axis (Guo). The living areas outside that of the Buddhist ritual spaces did not aim for symmetry and enjoyed relative freedom in their layout. 
                  </p>
               </desc>
